    <section id="qualification">
      <h2>Qualification &amp; Lead Scoring</h2>

      <p>Not all leads are equal. The distinction between a marketing qualified lead (MQL) and a sales qualified lead (SQL) is one of the most operationally important classifications in the revenue process.</p>

      <p>An <strong>MQL</strong> is a lead that has shown sufficient interest to warrant marketing's attention but hasn't been evaluated for sales-readiness — someone who downloaded an ebook, followed your LinkedIn page, or attended a webinar. An <strong>SQL</strong> is a lead that sales has reviewed and determined is ready for direct outreach.</p>

      <p>The transition from MQL to SQL typically requires meeting defined BANT criteria:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Budget:</strong> Does the prospect have budget allocated for this purchase?</li>
        <li><strong>Authority:</strong> Is this the decision-maker or a key influencer?</li>
        <li><strong>Need:</strong> Does the prospect have a specific, acknowledged problem your solution addresses?</li>
        <li><strong>Timeline:</strong> Are they evaluating solutions in a timeframe relevant to your pipeline goals?</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Lead scoring automates much of this evaluation. By assigning point values to behavioral signals (email opens, page visits, content downloads, demo requests) and demographic attributes (job title, company size, industry), scoring models surface high-probability leads for immediate outreach while routing lower-scoring contacts to nurture sequences. <a href="https://www.theinsightcollective.com/insights/lead-generation-trends" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AI-powered scoring tools are boosting conversion rates by up to 35%</a> in 2025–2026 by identifying buying intent signals that manual review would miss.</p>

      <p>The MQL-to-SQL handoff is where most programs leak value. <a href="https://learn.g2.com/lead-generation-statistics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">41% of B2B marketers</a> report difficulty aligning marketing-generated leads with sales expectations. When marketing's definition of "qualified" doesn't match what sales considers worth pursuing, leads pile up in CRM unworked.</p>

      <div class="callout warn">
        <strong>Speed matters:</strong> Leads contacted within 5 minutes are 21x more likely to qualify than those reached after 30 minutes, according to monday.com research. After one hour, qualification probability drops sharply. Response-time automation — triggered emails or immediate routing alerts — addresses this gap without requiring manual intervention.
      </div>
